	This is the home to all of my notes related to basic radar analysis. This is intended to gain familiarity with Radar technology for the purposes of an independent study class at Penn State University. These notes correspond with the book "Basic Radar Analysis" by Marvin C. Budge Jr. and Shawn R. German, which is cited in the bibliography below.
	
	\section*{Chapter 1}
	Radar is an acronym for Radio Detection and Ranging. Radar has been around since 1904, when Christian Hulsmeyer bounced waves off a a ship. Later during the 1920s, interest in this technology started to increase, and really started taking off during WWII, resulting in the widespread adoption we see today. \\

	Radar can use two types of signals:
	
	\begin{itemize}
  		\item Pulsed signals - transmit a sequence of radio frequency (RF) energy. An antenna connects to the transmitter as it sends signals out that connect to the receiver after a transmission phase. Transmit/receive (T/R) switches handle this switching functions. These are the most common types of signals. 
  		\item Continuous Waves (CW) - transmits a continuous signal, typically using two antennas. One for receiving and one for transmission.
		\end{itemize}
 
	Types of Radar
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Mono-Static: The transmitter and the receiver and placed together, making them compact. Which makes them the most common type.
		\item Bi-Static: The transmitter and the receiver are physically separated, often over long distances. These have more specific applications such as in aircraft or missiles. 
	\end{itemize}

	While the overall goal of radar is to detect targets and their location, they can also determine the distance between the two as well as the angle. This results in a location and velocity values, and sometimes higher derivatives of the location. 

	Radar operates in the radio band of the electromagnetic spectrum between 5 MHz and 300 GHz. Often times search radar will operate in C band, tracking radar in S-, KU-, K-, and KA bands, and instrumentation and short-range radar in Ka or above. The table below shows the bands as identified by IEEE. 

