	The most common way to measure range with radar is to measure the difference in time from transmission to reception of a pulse. Radio Frequencies (RF) travels at the speed of light. In the formulas listed below R is the range of the target, and c is the speed of light. To calculate the time to reach the target:

	\begin{equation}
		T_{out} = R / c
	\end{equation}
	
	The formula to calculate the time for a pulse to return from the target. 
	
	\begin{equation}
		T_{back} = R/ c
	\end{equation}
	
	The formula to calculate the time for the round trip for the radar pulse.
	
	\begin{equation}
		T_{R} = T_{out} + T_{back} = 2 R/c
	\end{equation}
	
	We can use this formula to determine the range, R, using the formula:
	
	\begin{equation}
		R = \frac{C T_R}{2}
	\end{equation}
	
	Slant Range is the measurement along a line between the radar and the target. This also applies from a radar using vertical projection to an object on the ground, this is known as ground range. It is also important to note that a common methodology of measuring range, is in terms of microseconds. Examine the example below:\
	
	\begin{equation}	
		R = \frac{c}{2}T_R	= \frac{3*10^8 m/s}{2} (T \mu s * 10^-6 s/\mu s) = 150_t s
	\end{equation}\
	
	Since pulsed radar issues a series of pulses that are all sent and received at different times, determining which signals correspond to one another is a difficult task. Often times the timer is reset every time a pulse is issued, which created ambiguity when measuring the range of radar. If the spacing of time between pulses is $T_{PRI}$, we can calculate unambiguous range using the following formula:
	
	\begin{equation}
		R_{amb} = \frac{C T_{PRI}}{2}	
	\end{equation}\
	
	If the target range is less than $R_{amb}$ then the radar can measure range unambiguously, and if that range is greater than $R_{amb}$ the radar can not measure this range unambiguously. PRI stands for pulse repetition interval. A way to avoid ambiguity is to choose a PRI  to exceed the range delay, of the longest reaching target, or transmit power further to minimize the possibility for long range detection of the radar. 
	
	


